<subSubSection lastPageId="27" lastPageNumber="232" pageId="26" pageNumber="231" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="26.[683,1198,163,1730]" box="[683,779,1498,1524]" pageId="26" pageNumber="231">
<emphasis box="[683,779,1498,1524]" italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="231">Ecology</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="26.[683,1198,163,1730]" pageId="26" pageNumber="231">
In 
<date box="[760,909,1533,1559]" pageId="26" pageNumber="231" value="1939-03">March 1939</date>
, a single specimen was shot at twilight on the forest trail leading to the Pyepat rest house, which was situated at an altitude of 
<quantity box="[897,1000,1635,1662]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.94" pageId="26" pageNumber="231" unit="m" value="1940.0">1,940 m</quantity>
(
<quantity box="[1021,1148,1635,1662]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.92024" pageId="26" pageNumber="231" unit="ft" value="6300.0">6,300 feet</quantity>
) on a small, steep sided, ridge in a forest clear- ing. The forest was temperate and included
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="27.[130,646,163,496]" pageId="27" pageNumber="232">
oaks, laurels and rhodendrons. The ground was damp, and the banks along the trail were covered with dense masses of ferns, mosses and begonias with an occasional 
<emphasis box="[130,226,300,326]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="232">Primula</emphasis>
, several species of orchid, gentians and many other plants. According to An- thony (1941), the ridge is a long, narrow intrusion of temperate flora and fauna into the tropical ecology found in the two river valleys.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
